#X text 38 473 The ELSE library has a simple and straight forward Ring Modulation object called [rm~]. It uses [osc~] as the modulator and the frequency input is given as the argument or via the right inlet. It's worth noting it treats a 0 Hz input as a bypass. This is important because at 0 Hz \, the oscillator outputs whatever amplitude value according to that instantaneous phase \, and it won't likely be "1" \, so you have an undesired gain change., f 71;
#X obj 833 47 declare -path else;
#X text 38 19 In this example \, we have a sample as the carrier instead of an oscillator \, which illustrates the usage of amplitude modulation as an effects processor rather than a "synthesis technique"., f 60;
#X text 38 389 Note how the AM still presents the original sound's sine components \, but the generated side band frequencies interfere with them \, so it's more common to see an AM as a tremolo effect (that we'll see later). The RM example may sound more interesting \, because it removes the original sine components., f 71;
